CONTAGIOUS EQUINE METRITIS - USA (KENTUCKY)
*******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
See Also
Contagious equine metritis - USA (California) 980109220214
Date: Sun, 22 Feb 1998 16:51:14 -0600
From: Martin Hugh-Jones <mehj2020@vt8200.vetmed.lsu.edu>
Source: OIE Report 20 February 1998

Emergency report: Date of last previously reported outbreak - December 1997.
Text of a communication received on 16 February 1998 from Dr J.M. Arnoldi,
Deputy Administrator, Veterinary Services, United States Department of
Agriculture, Washington, DC:
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 28 January 1998.
Estimated date of first infection: 21 January 1998.
Location: Fayette County, Kentucky
No. of outbreaks: 1
Total number of animals in the outbreak:
susceptible, 5
cases, 1 (one adult mare)
deaths, 0
destroyed, 0
slaughtered, 0
Diagnosis: two adult mares were being tested to qualify as test mares for an
imported stallion. _Taylorella equigenitalis_ was cultured from one of the
mares. There were no clinical signs in this mare.
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: National Veterinary Services
Laboratory, Ames, Iowa.
B. Diagnostic tests used: fluorescent antibody of culture isolate and
biochemical characteristics.
C. Causal agent: organism appears similar to the organism isolated in the
case reported on 30 December 1997 (see Disease Information, 11 [1, 4).
Epidemiology:
A. Source of agent / origin of infection: to date there is no
epidemiological relationship to the case reported on 30 December.
B. Mode of spread: unknown at this time. Epidemiology being performed.
C. Other epidemiological details: an adult jack and another adult mare are
also on the same farm and are being tested for contagious equine metritis.
Results pending. Animals identified in trace-outs and trace-backs will also
be tested.
Control measures during reporting period: quarantine movement control and
other precautions at frontiers and inside country. The mare will be treated
in accordance with standard treatment procedures.
--
ProMED-mail
